        "For millennia, the high glaciers of Europe, Asia, and the Americas have acted as unlikely custodians of human history. Extreme cold arrests decomposition so thoroughly that organic materials preserved in ice can emerge, centuries later, in near-perfect condition. Scientists and archaeologists have long known that glaciers advance and retreat, but the pace at which they are currently receding has transformed them, in the words of one glaciologist, into \"libraries that are burning faster than we can read them.\"",
