        "Walk into almost any secondhand bookshop and you will notice the same apparent contradiction: the shelves are impossibly full, the prices are low, and yet the proprietor seems, if not exactly prosperous, at least stubbornly solvent. The economics of the trade have puzzled retail analysts for decades. In a sector where margins on new books are notoriously thin and large chains have repeatedly collapsed, the small, chaotic, independently owned used bookshop continues to survive.",
        "Part of the explanation lies in the structure of the supply chain. A new-book retailer must buy stock at a wholesale price set by the publisher, bear the cost of unsold returns, and compete on price with online platforms that have perfected the logistics of deep discounting. The secondhand dealer, by contrast, acquires stock at close to zero marginal cost, prices according to perceived demand, and carries no obligation to return unsold items.",
        "The idiosyncratic organisation of most secondhand shops is not, as it might appear, a symptom of neglect. Many proprietors have spent years developing elaborate personal filing systems that allow them to locate any volume within minutes. The apparent disorder is, in many cases, a deliberate deterrent to browsing customers who might disturb a carefully maintained arrangement.",
        "The internet age posed what seemed an existential threat. When platforms such as AbeBooks and Alibris made it possible to search millions of secondhand titles globally and have them delivered within days, commentators predicted the death of the physical shop. The browsable, serendipitous experience of the bricks-and-mortar store was supposed to be no match for the algorithmic efficiency of online aggregators.",
