        "On warm summer evenings in the forests of the Great Smoky Mountains, a phenomenon occurs that draws thousands of visitors each year: thousands of fireflies begin to flash simultaneously, their cold bioluminescent light pulsing in waves across the dark understorey. The spectacle is neither random nor orchestrated by any single individual. It is, instead, an emergent property of local interactions repeated across an entire population.",
        "The species responsible, Photinus carolinus, is one of only a handful of firefly species in the world known to synchronise. The male emits a distinctive pattern of six rapid flashes followed by a pause of roughly eight seconds. Females perched in the vegetation respond with a delayed double flash. Mating success depends on the male's signal being both distinctive and detectable against background noise.",
