        "Several of these joint forms achieve structural effects that Western carpentry never developed. The kigumi, a box joint used in timber framing, gains strength as the wood it joins expands with seasonal moisture, since expansion drives the interlocking fingers more tightly together rather than splitting them apart. It is a solution that exploits the material properties of wood rather than working against them, converting what Western builders have long regarded as a liability into a structural asset.",
        "This training philosophy reflects a deeper epistemology. In the miyadaiku tradition, knowledge is not primarily propositional but procedural: it resides in the hands and the eye rather than in written instructions or verbal descriptions. A master carpenter teaching a joinery technique will not explain why a certain angle is correct but will guide the apprentice's hands repeatedly through the motion until the geometry becomes, in the practitioner's own phrase, \"something the body knows.\"",
        "The computational demands of this geometry were, for most of the tradition's history, met by a single instrument: the sashigane, a graduated L-shaped steel square whose two arms are calibrated in different scales. A skilled carpenter using the sashigane can calculate the angles required for any roof pitch, any compound joint, and any tapered element without recourse to trigonometric tables. The instrument encodes geometric relationships that took European architects centuries to formalise algebraically.",
